<dl id="n26092e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26092e">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26092e"> 92(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hosey <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n26092e"><li>FW 553.34 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n26092e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n26092e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n26092e">MS missing <a name="rAd10dash" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rBd17dash">Usage</a></ms> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd17.htm#n26092e">Draft: III&sect;3B.17</a>'</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">At Nuncoton in 1440 a nun informed Bishop Alnwick that two old nuns lay in the fermery and took their meals in the convent&apos;s cellar &ldquo;and likewise the infirm, the weak minded (imbecilles) and they that are in their seynies do eat in the same cellar&rdquo;. Complaints of the presence of idiots were fairly frequent. It is easy to understand the exasperation of Thetford over the case of Dorothy Sturges, when one finds Dame Katherine Mitford complaining at the same visitation that Elizabeth Haukeforth is &ldquo;<i>aliquando lunatica;</i>&rdquo;; but a few years later Agnes <mark>Hosey</mark>, described as &ldquo;ideota,&rdquo; gave testimony with her sisters at Easebourne and excited no adverse comment. In an age when faith and superstition went hand in hand a mad nun might even bring glory to her house <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <small> Eileen Edna Power, <a name="MLEN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MLEN"><cite title="source">Medieval English Nunneries</cite></a> (1922) 33</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
